"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838610","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Department does not hold the data requested. The data needed to make robust estimates of the number of recipients of Support for Mortgage Interest (SMI) at geographies smaller than Government Office Region is not available to Departmental analysts.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-02-20T12:39:49.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838610/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838610/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-07","Support for Mortgage Interest: Gower","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many households in Gower were in receipt of support for mortgage interest in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Tonia Antoniazzi","Gower","Tonia Antoniazzi","127430"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838611","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Home Office monitors closely the performance of asylum support application decision making and has a range of targets for processing support applications depending on the nature of the application being made. However information on processing times is not recorded in a format suitable for publication and there are no plans to publish such statistics at this time.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:28:32.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838611/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838611/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-07","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will publish the data held by her Department on the average length of time taken to make a decision on an asylum support application.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","127431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838612","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Home Office monitors closely the performance of asylum support application decision making and has a range of targets for processing support applications depending on the nature of the application being made. However information on processing times is not recorded in a format suitable for publication and there are no plans to publish such statistics at this time.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:18:52.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838612/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838612/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-07","Asylum","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make it her policy to publishing data on length of time taken for decisions to be made on applications for asylum support on a quarterly basis.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","127432"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838613","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>National Health Service properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced.</p><p> </p><p>Operational costs related to property, which include business rates, are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS. The Government committed to backing the NHS’s Five Year Forward View plan with a £10 billion a year real terms increase in funding by 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no such assessment.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","127434","2018-02-20T12:14:16.99Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838613/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838613/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838613/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-07","NHS Trusts: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of providing NHS Trusts with additional funding to offset business rates costs.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","127433"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838614","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-02-20","<p>National Health Service properties, like almost all other buildings occupied by public bodies, have been subject to non-domestic rates since they were introduced.</p><p> </p><p>Operational costs related to property, which include business rates, are taken into account at spending reviews in determining the overall level of funding for the NHS. The Government committed to backing the NHS’s Five Year Forward View plan with a £10 billion a year real terms increase in funding by 2020/21.</p><p> </p><p>There has been no such assessment.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay","127433","2018-02-20T12:14:17.053Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838614/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838614/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-02-07","NHS Trusts: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what recent assessment he has made of the potential merits of allowing NHS Trusts to claim relief on business rates.","false","Biography information for Joan Ryan","Enfield North","Joan Ryan","127434"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838615","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>Some funding for apprenticeships comes from employers themselves. We ask those employers who do not pay the levy, or have insufficient funds in their apprenticeship service account, to make a 10 per cent contribution towards the costs of apprenticeship off-the-job training and assessment. We waive this co-investment for smaller employers who take on 16 to 18 year olds, disadvantaged apprentices, care leavers or those with learning disabilities.</p><p> </p><p>Her Majesty's Treasury collects the apprenticeship levy and the Devolved Administrations receive a proportionate share. In England, Her Majesty's Treasury has agreed the apprenticeships budget with the department. We are investing in skills across the whole of England and by 2019-20 the annual spending on apprenticeships in England will reach £2.45 billion, which is double that spent in 2010-11.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-02-20T15:04:45.853Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838615/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838615/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-07","Apprentices: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if it remains the Government’s policy to fund the entire apprenticeship programme for levy and non-levy paying employers in England from the proceeds of the apprenticeship levy.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","127435"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838616","Department for Education","false","2018-02-20","<p>The procurement was conducted in accordance with the Public Contracts Regulations 2015.</p><p> </p><p>Contracts for the delivery of non-levy apprenticeship training were not awarded on the basis of Ofsted ratings, but on the basis of an Education and Skills Funding Agency (ESFA) assessment of information supplied by providers against a defined set of criteria. As set out in the Invitation to Tender, the ESFA did not make initial offers of awards where providers did not meet the Award Threshold, which is the minimum score, or where the total contract value was below the minimum award of £200,000.</p><p> </p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2018-02-20T15:40:56.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838616/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838616/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838616/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-02-07","Apprentices: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, for what reasons the Education and Skills Funding Agency did not award non-levy apprenticeship contracts to all (a) good and (b) outstanding specialist training providers and colleges in its recent procurement.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","127436"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838617","Home Office","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Home Office closely monitors the length of stay of asylum seekers in Initial Accommodation and aims to move people to Dispersed Accommodation within 19 days. However, some stay in Initial Accommodation for shorter or longer periods depending on their individual needs. Information on the length of stay of people in Initial Accommodation is not currently recorded in a format suitable for publication.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-02-20T12:27:12.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838617/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838617/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-02-07","Asylum: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information her Department collects on the length of stay in initial accommodation for people applying for Section 95, non-emergency, asylum support.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","127437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838618","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-02-20","<p>The Universal Credit telephone numbers previously used by the Department were not premium rate numbers and it is misleading to refer to them in this way. The 0345 numbers that were in use were charged at local rate and are included in the call packages of most mobile and landline phone deals.</p><p> </p><p>Any customer who raised a concern about the costs of calling the Department was offered a call back. We have no evidence that people did not call because they believed the service was a premium rate number.</p><p> </p><p>To ensure that customers dial the correct numbers, the Department has embarked on an exercise to update all its products. The Department’s electronic media, such as SMS text messages and Gov.uk website, were updated as the new freephone numbers were introduced. System generated notifications for Universal Credit Full Service were updated on 28 November. System notifications for Universal Credit Live Service were updated between 28 November and 31 January 2018.</p><p> </p><p>During the period that our products were being updated, any calls to a 0345 number were played a message that told them that that number had been replaced with a Freephone number, whilst giving them the new Freephone number to use.</p><p> </p><p>The current monthly cost to the Department for playing the recorded messages to provide the new freephone numbers is approximately £300.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma","127389 ; 127440 ; 127442","2018-02-20T11:45:14.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838618/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838618/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-02-07","Universal Credit: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions,  what estimate her Department has made of the number of people who did not call the Universal Credit helpline as a result of believing that it was a premium rate number.","false","Biography information for Mike Amesbury","Weaver Vale","Mike Amesbury","127438"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838619","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-02-22","<p>The Building Safety Programme has been working with local authorities and building owners across England to identify properties that might be at risk. For all of those high-rise buildings that have been confirmed as having aluminium composite material cladding that does not meet the limited combustibility requirements set out in current building regulations guidance, the relevant fire and rescue service has been notified. We have worked with local authorities, housing associations, fire and rescue services and building owners to ensure that immediate steps are taken to make buildings safe.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2018-02-22T17:02:28.66Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838619/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/838619/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-02-07","High Rise Flats: Liverpool Walton","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of the safety of high rise tower blocks in Liverpool Walton constituency.","false","Biography information for Dan Carden","Liverpool, Walton","Dan Carden","127439"
